properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: An intense low pressure system over New England will approach the Maritimes today and cross the region on Friday. A band of very strong southeasterly winds gusting to 90 km/h is continuing to spread across Nova Scotia today and will reach the eastern Mainland and Cape Breton this afternoon. Higher than normal water levels and heavy surf can be expected along the Atlantic coast and areas near Northumberland Strait today, especially near high tide. Winds will diminish and become southerly later today, starting in the southwest near noon and over eastern areas later this afternoon or this evening. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. An area of high pressure situated over the Arctic Ocean and an intense low pressure system over the Gulf of Alaska will continue to produce conditions favourable for strong, gusty winds near the Richardson Mountains. The strong winds, falling snow and existing snow pack will combine to produce blizzard conditions through at least Friday. ### Travel is expected to be extremely hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 4 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. An intense low pressure system over New England will approach the Maritimes today and cross the region on Friday. A band of very strong easterly winds will continue to spread across New Brunswick today. Over areas near the coast, these winds are forecast to gust to 90 km/h. Winds will diminish by this afternoon over southern regions and late this evening in the Bay of Chaleur region. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. A disturbance tracking northeastward out of the Northwest Territories will bring snow to the Baker Lake area today and tonight. Snow, at times heavy, is expected to develop around midday today and persist during the evening before tapering off to light snow overnight. Snowfall accumulations of 10 to 15 cm will be possible by Friday morning. A second disturbance is forecast to enter the area on Friday with another 2 to 4 cm of wet snow possible. In addition to the snow strong southeasterly winds gusting at times to 70 km/h are expected today resulting in some blowing snow. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Storm Surge Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Higher than normal water levels with large waves are expected near the coast. Higher than normal water levels and large waves near the coast late today. Warning of potential breaking sea conditions and overwash issued jointly by Fisheries and Oceans Canada (Science) and the Meteorological Service of Canada - Quebec Region on 2019-10-16. An intense low pressure system moving up the U.S. east coast will give strong to high winds today over the areas below. The combination of these winds and the current run of medium tidal ranges could produce minor breaking sea conditions along the coast in the vicinity of the following localities, on the dates and at the times specified (Eastern Daylight Time). Rimouski - Mont-Joli : 2019-10-17, from 03:00 PM to 07:00 PM. Matane: 2019-10-17, from 03:00 PM to 07:00 PM. Forillon Park - Gaspe - Percé: 2019-10-17, from 03:00 PM to 08:00 PM. New-Carlisle - Chandler: 2019-10-17, from 03:00 PM to 07:00 PM. Baie-Comeau: 2019-10-17, from 03:00 PM to 07:00 PM. Baie-Trinite - Port-Cartier: 2019-10-17, from 03:00 PM to 07:00 PM. ### Coastal flooding is possible along the shoreline. Coastal erosion is possible in vulnerable areas. Storm surge warnings are issued when water levels pose a threat to coastal regions. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.
